So the Day of Archaeology has finally dawned and my chance to talk about archaeological conservation in a commercial unit has arrived.Â  I had hoped that I was going to be called out onto site to lift some vulnerable but really valuable find and save the day.Â  The reality is of course much more mundane, but probably as or more important, as today I'm going to spend theÂ  day investigating objects for publication.

People forget that archaeology is not just about digging but also disseminating information.Â  Archaeological conservation can be vital to that process, as it reveals what objects are and what they look like.Â  So I am currently working on the air abrasive cleaning of Roman iron.Â  The air abrasive is a brilliant bit of kit as it is a micro-sandblaster and sometimes is the only thing that can remove thick, hard and dense corrosion to reveal the object.

[caption id="attachment_1169" align="alignleft" width="406" caption="Iron object"]<a href="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/a-day-in-the-life-of-an-archeological-conservator/part_cleaned/" rel="attachment wp-att-1169"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1169 " title="part_cleaned" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/part_cleaned-580x389.jpg" alt="" width="406" height="272" /></a>[/caption]

